-54"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-54">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation news"><a href="/wiki/Evan_Thomas" title="Evan Thomas">Thomas, Evan</a> (July 2, 1984). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,926644,00.html">"Trying to Win the Peace"</a>. <i><a href="/wiki/Time_(magazine)" title="Time (magazine)">Time</a></i>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AGeraldine+Ferraro&amp;rft.atitle=Trying+to+Win+the+Peace&amp;rft.au=Thomas%2C+Evan&amp;rft.date=1984-07-02&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Time&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.time.com%2Ftime%2Fmagazine%2Farticle%2F0%2C9171%2C926644%2C00.html&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span></span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-55"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-55">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Goldman and Fuller, <i>The Quest for the Presidency 1984</i>, p. 208.</span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-pol071207-56"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-pol071207_56-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-pol071207_56-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation news">Glass, Andrew (July 12, 2007). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0707/4891.html">"Ferraro joins Democratic ticket July&#160;12, 1984"</a>. <i><a href="/wiki/The_Politico" class="mw-redirect" title="The Politico">The Politico</a></i><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap">June 8,</span> 2008</span>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AGeraldine+Ferraro&amp;rft.atitle=Ferraro+joins+Democratic+ticket+July+12%2C+1984&amp;rft.aufirst=Andrew&amp;rft.aulast=Glass&amp;rft.date=2007-07-12&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=The+Politico&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.politico.com%2Fnews%2Fstories%2F0707%2F4891.html&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span></span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-ap-mgh-57"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-ap-mgh_57-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-ap-mgh_57-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-ap-mgh_57-2"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-ap-mgh_57-3"><sup><i><b>d</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation news">Fouhy, Beth; Lindsay, Jay (March 26, 2011). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.boston.com/news/local/massachusetts/articles/2011/03/26/first_vp_candidate_geraldine_ferraro_dies_at_75/?page=full">"First female VP candidate Geraldine Ferraro dies at 75"</a>. <i><a href="/wiki/The_Boston_Globe" title="The Boston Globe">The Boston Globe</a></i>. Associated Press<span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap">May 30,</span> 2014</span>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AGeraldine+Ferraro&amp;rft.atitle=First+female+VP+candidate+Geraldine+Ferraro+dies+at+75&amp;rft.au=Fouhy%2C+Beth&amp;rft.au=Lindsay%2C+Jay&amp;rft.date=2011-03-26&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=The+Boston+Globe&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.boston.com%2Fnews%2Flocal%2Fmassachusetts%2Farticles%2F2011%2F03%2F26%2Ffirst_vp_candidate_geraldine_ferraro_dies_at_75%2F%3Fpage%3Dfull&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span></span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-58"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-58">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Goldman and Fuller, <i>The Quest for the Presidency 1984</i>, p. 212.</span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-59"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-59">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Although Ferraro was the first woman to be on a major-party ticket for one of the nation\'s two highest offices, she was not the first woman to receive an <a href="/wiki/Electoral_college" title="Electoral college">electoral college</a> vote. That woman was <a href="/wiki/Theodora_Nathan" class="mw-redirect" title="Theodora Nathan">Theodora Nathan</a>, a <a href="/wiki/United_States_Libertarian_Party" class="mw-redirect" title="United States Libertarian Party">Libertarian</a> Vice-Presidential candidate who got the support of <a href="/wiki/Roger_MacBride" title="Roger MacBride">Roger MacBride</a>, a <a href="/wiki/Faithless_elector" title="Faithless elector">faithless elector</a> from <a href="/wiki/Virginia" title="Virginia">Virginia</a> who in 1972, voted for her instead of the pledged <a href="/wiki/Spiro_Agnew" title="Spiro Agnew">Spiro Agnew</a>. However, Ferraro was the first woman to receive more than one electoral vote. See <cite class="citation web"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20090320201043/http://www.cawp.rutgers.edu/fast_facts/levels_of_office/documents/prescand.pdf">"Women Presidential and Vice Presidential Candidates: A Selected List"</a> <span style="font-size:85%;">(PDF)</span>. <a href="/wiki/Rutgers_University" title="Rutgers University">Rutgers University</a> Center for American Women and Politics. 2008. Archived from <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.cawp.rutgers.edu/fast_facts/levels_of_office/documents/prescand.pdf">the original</a> <span style="font-size:85%;">(PDF)</span> on March 20, 2009<span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap">January 23,</span> 2009</span>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AGeraldine+Ferraro&amp;rft.btitle=Women+Presidential+and+Vice+Presidential+Candidates%3A+A+Selected+List&amp;rft.date=2008&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.pub=Rutgers+University+Center+for+American+Women+and+Politics&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.cawp.rutgers.edu%2Ffast_facts%2Flevels_of_office%2Fdocuments%2Fprescand.pdf&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span></span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-60"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-60">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Mention is occasionally made of <a href="/wiki/Al_Smith" title="Al Smith">Al Smith</a>, who was the Democratic presidential nominee in the <a href="/wiki/United_States_presidential_election,_1928" title="United States presidential election, 1928">1928 election</a>, as the first Italian American to run on a major party national ticket. But Smith was only one-quarter Italian in heritage, was not known by an Italian surname, and was generally identified as an Irish American. While his Roman Catholic religion was certainly a major issue in the election, his partial Italian heritage was not. See <cite class="citation news">Slayton, Robert A. (December 10, 2011). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://campaignstops.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/12/10/when-a-catholic-terrified-the-heartland/?_r=0">"When a Catholic Terrified the Heartland"</a>. <i>The New York Times</i>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AGeraldine+Ferraro&amp;rft.atitle=When+a+Catholic+Terrified+the+Heartland&amp;rft.aufirst=Robert+A.&amp;rft.aulast=Slayton&amp;rft.date=2011-12-10&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=The+New+York+Times&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fcampaignstops.blogs.nytimes.com%2F2011%2F12%2F10%2Fwhen-a-catholic-terrified-the-heartland%2F%3F_r%3D0&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span> The large majority of sources consider Ferraro to have been the first Italian American to achieve this distinction. See <cite class="citation news">Martin, Douglas (March 26, 2011). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2011/03/27/us/politics/27geraldine-ferraro.html?_r=0">"She Ended the Men\'s Club of National Politics"</a>. <i>The New York Times</i>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AGeraldine+Ferraro&amp;rft.atitle=She+Ended+the+Men%27s+Club+of+National+Politics&amp;rft.aufirst=Douglas&amp;rft.aulast=Martin&amp;rft.date=2011-03-26&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=The+New+York+Times&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.nytimes.com%2F2011%2F03%2F27%2Fus%2Fpolitics%2F27geraldine-ferraro.html%3F_r%3D0&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span>; <cite class="citation news">Schudel, Matt (March 26, 2011). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/obituaries/geraldine-a-ferraro-first-woman-major-party-candidate-on-presidential-ticket-dies-at-75/2011/03/26/AFLyheeB_story.html">"Geraldine A. Ferraro, first woman major-party candidate on presidential ticket, dies at 75"</a>. <i>The Washington Post</i>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AGeraldine+Ferraro&amp;rft.atitle=Geraldine+A.+Ferraro%2C+first+woman+major-party+candidate+on+presidential+ticket%2C+dies+at+75&amp;rft.aufirst=Matt&amp;rft.aulast=Schudel&amp;rft.date=2011-03-26&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=The+Washington+Post&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.washingtonpost.com%2Flocal%2Fobituaries%2Fgeraldine-a-ferraro-first-woman-major-party-candidate-on-presidential-ticket-dies-at-75%2F2011%2F03%2F26%2FAFLyheeB_story.html&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span>; <cite class="citation news">Woo, Elaine (March 26, 2011). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://articles.latimes.com/2011/mar/26/local/la-me-geraldine-ferraro-20110327">"Geraldine Ferraro dies at 75; shattered political barrier for women as vice presidential nominee in 1984"</a>. <i>Los Angeles Times</i>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AGeraldine+Ferraro&amp;rft.atitle=Geraldine+Ferraro+dies+at+75%3B+shattered+political+barrier+for+women+as+vice+presidential+nominee+in+1984&amp;rft.aufirst=Elaine&amp;rft.aulast=Woo&amp;rft.date=2011-03-26&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Los+Angeles+Times&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Farticles.latimes.com%2F2011%2Fmar%2F26%2Flocal%2Fla-me-geraldine-ferraro-20110327&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span>; and <cite class="citation news">McGuire, Bill (March 27, 2011). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/geraldine-ferraro-dies-75-woman-vice-president-candidate-remembered/story?id=13228533">"Geraldine Ferraro, First Woman VP Candidate, Dies at 75"</a>. ABC News.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AGeraldine+Ferraro&amp;rft.atitle=Geraldine+Ferraro%2C+First+Woman+VP+Candidate%2C+Dies+at+75&amp;rft.aufirst=Bill&amp;rft.aulast=McGuire&amp;rft.date=2011-03-27&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fabcnews.go.com%2FPolitics%2Fgeraldine-ferraro-dies-75-woman-vice-president-candidate-remembered%2Fstory%3Fid%3D13228533&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span></span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-cq18-61"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-cq18_61-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-cq18_61-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-cq18_61-2"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-cq18_61-3"><sup><i><b>d</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class="reference-text"><i>Congress and the Nation 1981\xe2\x80\x931984</i>, pp. 18\xe2\x80\x9320.</span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-hdpe-62"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-hdpe_62-0"><sup